__data__.text: american revolution: the american revolution was an ideological and political movement in the thirteen colonies that led to the american revolutionary war and the establishment of the united states of america

thirteen colonies: the thirteen colonies were affected by the royal proclamation of 1763  leading to tensions with settlers  fur traders  and land speculators over westward migration and territorial restrictions<SEP>the thirteen colonies were the british colonies in america where the american revolution took place  leading to their independence
british america: british america refers to the territories in america under british rule during the time of the american revolution
american revolutionary war: the american revolutionary war was the armed conflict between the thirteen colonies and great britain  resulting in american independence
battles of lexington and concord: the battles of lexington and concord marked the beginning of the american revolutionary war on april 19  1775
leaders of the american revolution: leaders of the american revolution were colonial separatist figures who advocated for independence from british rule and played key roles in the revolutionary war
second continental congress: the second continental congress represented the colonies during the american revolution  forming the continental army and declaring independence
george washington: george washington was appointed as the commander in chief of the continental army during the american revolutionary war and later became the first president of the united states
declaration of independence: the declaration of independence was adopted by the second continental congress in 1776  declaring the thirteen colonies  independence from great britain
treaty of paris: the treaty of paris in 1783 officially ended the american revolutionary war and recognized the independence of the united states from britain

france: france is the primary funder of the anglo french war of 1778 1783 through loans  leading to a debt crisis and financial challenges<SEP>france supported the american colonies during the revolutionary war  contributing to the eventual victory of the colonists over the british<SEP>france was defeated by great britain during the french and indian war  leading to territorial acquisitions by the british
loyalists: loyalists were individuals who remained loyal to the british crown during the american revolution and later migrated to other british territories
british parliament: british parliament imposed taxes and regulations on the thirteen colonies  leading to tensions and resistance
stamp act congress: the stamp act congress in 1765 protested against taxation without representation  asserting colonial rights
townshend acts: the townshend acts of 1767 heightened tensions by imposing duties on various goods imported to the colonies
boston massacre: the boston massacre in 1770 resulted in british troops killing protesters  escalating anti british sentiments
boston tea party: the boston tea party in 1773 was a protest against british taxation policies  leading to increased tensions
sons of liberty: the sons of liberty were activists who protested british policies  including the boston tea party
gaspee affair: the gaspee affair in 1772 involved the destruction of a british customs ship  symbolizing resistance to british authority
first continental congress: the first continental congress in 1774 united colonial delegates to address grievances and coordinate resistance against british policies
carpenters  hall: carpenters  hall in philadelphia hosted the first continental congress  a significant event in colonial resistance
articles of confederation: the articles of confederation were debated by the second continental congress as a precursor to the u s  constitution  aiming for self governance
lee resolution: the lee resolution of 1776 declared the thirteen colonies  support for independence  paving the way for the declaration of independence
thomas jefferson: thomas jefferson played a key role in drafting the declaration of independence  embodying principles of liberty and equality
marquis de lafayette: marquis de lafayette supported the american cause during the revolutionary war  aiding in key victories
capt  levi preston: capt  levi preston is a colonist from danvers  massachusetts  who expresses the sentiment of self governance and rebellion against england
charles ii: charles ii attempts to bring new england under direct english control  leading to opposition from the colonists
james ii: james ii  along with charles ii  attempts to consolidate control over new england  facing fierce opposition from the colonists
edmund andros: edmund andros is appointed royal governor over new england  triggering resentment due to his restrictive rule and abridgment of rights
william and mary: william and mary grant new charters to the new england colonies  restoring local democratic self government after the glorious revolution
british empire: the british empire transitions into a constitutional monarchy after the glorious revolution  with a system of governance involving the king in parliament and cabinet ministers
house of lords: the house of lords is composed of aristocrats who inherit seats  playing a role in the governance of the british empire
house of commons: the house of commons is elected by the gentry and merchants  providing majority support for cabinet ministers to govern effectively in the british empire

navigation acts: the navigation acts are a series of laws passed by parliament to regulate colonial trade and restrict certain commodities  impacting the economic relationship between the thirteen colonies and britain
colonists: colonists in the thirteen colonies rebel against england s control and seek greater autonomy  leading to significant historical events
king charles i: king charles i is executed during the english civil war  leading to support for the commonwealth government in the puritan colonies of new england
king philip s war: king philip s war involves conflicts between the new england colonies and native american tribes  contributing to the development of a unique american identity
stuart restoration: the stuart restoration of 1660 sees massachusetts not recognizing charles ii as the legitimate king immediately after his coronation  showcasing resistance to english authority
dominion of new england: the dominion of new england is established by james ii to consolidate control over new england colonies  leading to colonial resentment and eventual revolt
glorious revolution of 1688: the glorious revolution of 1688 sees the removal of james ii from power and the restoration of colonial self governance in new england
boston revolt: the 1689 boston revolt overthrows dominion rule in new england  leading to the reassertion of colonial governments and restoration of local control
robert middlekauff: historian robert middlekauff notes the self governing nature of americans before the american revolution  reflecting a practice of salutary neglect by the british monarchy

british government: the british government fielded soldiers and contributed to the war effort during the french and indian war  leading to territorial acquisitions and decisions regarding garrisoning troops in north america
colonies: the colonies contributed money to the war effort during the french and indian war and were involved in conflicts with native americans and foreign populations in newly acquired territories
mississippi river: the mississippi river served as a geographical boundary for territorial acquisitions and conflicts during the french and indian war
bute ministry: the bute ministry made decisions regarding the permanent garrisoning of soldiers in north america and the stationing of british army officers with full pay
native americans: native americans were involved in conflicts with white colonists and british soldiers in newly acquired territories  leading to the need for defense and prevention of conflicts
appalachian mountains: the appalachian mountains served as a geographical boundary and were designated as an indian reserve closed to white settlement by the royal proclamation of 1763
pontiac s war: pontiac s war was launched by native americans in response to increased migration beyond the appalachian mountains and the removal of the french threat

french and indian war: the french and indian war was a significant conflict involving the british government  colonies  and native americans  leading to territorial acquisitions and decisions regarding troop garrisoning in north america
british regulars: british regulars were part of the soldiers fielded by the british government during the french and indian war  contributing to the war effort and territorial acquisitions

colonial volunteers: colonial volunteers were part of the soldiers fielded during the french and indian war  aiding the british government and participating in conflicts with native americans and foreign populations
grenville ministry: the grenville ministry issued the royal proclamation of 1763  designating territories and influencing westward migration and conflicts with settlers and fur traders
french revolution: the french revolution was a period of political and societal change in france  marked by significant events such as the estates general of 1789 and the coup of 18 brumaire in 1799

estates general: the estates general is summoned to address tax and representation issues  leading to debates and demands for reform<SEP>the estates general of 1789 was a pivotal event that marked the beginning of the french revolution  showcasing the political tensions and changes in france
coup of 18 brumaire: the coup of 18 brumaire in 1799 marked the end of the french revolution  signifying a shift in political power in france
ancien r gime: the ancien r gime refers to the old regime in france  characterized by social  political  and economic factors that led to the revolution
louis xvi: louis xvi was the king of france during the french revolution  whose actions and decisions influenced the course of events
national assembly: the national assembly was formed by the representatives of the third estate during the french revolution  showcasing a shift in political power
storming of the bastille: the storming of the bastille on 14 july was a significant event during the french revolution  symbolizing the people s uprising against the monarchy
reign of terror: the reign of terror was a period during the french revolution marked by mass executions and political repression under the committee of public safety
estates general of 1789: the estates general of 1789 was a pivotal event that marked the beginning of the french revolution  showcasing the political tensions and changes in france
committee of public safety: the committee of public safety played a key role during the reign of terror in the french revolution  overseeing political repression and mass executions
french first republic: the french first republic replaced the monarchy during the french revolution  signifying a shift in political structure in france
directory: the directory was established after the reign of terror  replacing the committee of public safety and marking a period of transition in french governance
thermidorian reaction: the thermidorian reaction marked the end of the reign of terror during the french revolution  leading to a shift in political power and a decrease in radical measures
napoleon bonaparte: napoleon bonaparte became the first consul of france after the coup of 18 brumaire  consolidating power and leading to significant changes in french history
tax farmers: tax farmers are contracted to collect taxes  keeping a portion as personal profit  impacting the tax burden on peasants
nobility: the nobility benefits from exemptions  influencing the distribution of the tax burden and participating in conflicts over tax laws
church: the church benefits from exemptions  affecting the tax burden distribution and participating in conflicts over tax laws
peasants: peasants bear the main tax burden due to exemptions enjoyed by the nobility and church  leading to tensions and conflicts
calonne: calonne proposes tax reforms and faces rejection by the nobility and parlements  leading to a financial crisis and political conflict
brienne: brienne faces challenges in implementing new taxes and reforms  leading to political unrest and the summoning of the estates general
tax laws: tax laws are difficult to reform due to the need for registration with regional judicial bodies or parlements  leading to challenges in implementing new tax policies
anglo french war of 1778 1783: the anglo french war of 1778 1783 is primarily funded by france through loans  impacting the country s financial situation and debt crisis
debt crisis: france faces a debt crisis by borrowing heavily post the anglo french war of 1778 1783  leading to financial challenges and the need for reforms
assembly of notables: the assembly of notables rejects new taxes proposed by calonne  leading to political tensions and the demand for approval by the estates general
jacques necker: jacques necker replaces brienne as the french finance minister  facing challenges in addressing the financial crisis and political unrest
parlement of paris: the parlement of paris rules on the format of the estates general  impacting the representation and voting structure of the clergy  nobility  and third estate
society of thirty: the society of thirty campaigns for increased third estate representation and individual voting rights  influencing the public debate and political activism
abb  siey s: abb  siey s issues influential pamphlets advocating for the third estate s representation and denouncing the privilege of the clergy and nobility
jean joseph mounier: jean joseph mounier is an activist supporting increased third estate representation and individual voting rights  organizing regional meetings and petitions
antoine barnave: antoine barnave is an activist advocating for increased third estate representation and individual voting rights  contributing to the public debate and demands for reform
maximilien robespierre: maximilien robespierre is an activist supporting increased third estate representation and individual voting rights  engaging in political activism and literature
